title: ‘What a scammer’: Airbnb host demands guest cancel their reservation after claiming the room will not be ready in time, guest refuses when discovering they were already charged for it
description: There is something about businesses that allow random people to provide service to other random people, that is simply a recipe for disaster. Airbnb, Uber, DoorDash, etc – In theory, they are all great business models that allow people to make money without needing to maintain a whole business. Interested in becoming a taxi driver on your days off? Sign up for Uber. Want to rent out a unit no one is using? You don't have to register it as a hotel, you can just sign up for Airbnb. Simple as that.Except when it's not.The fact that these people are doing these 'side gigs', means that some of them are not 100% committed to it, and are definitely not committed to satisfying their customers. Because of this lack of commitment, customer service has to work overtime to ensure that people do not take advantage of each other, especially those who attempt to scam others for money.Take the Airbnb host as an example of someone who didn't really care about the business, and tried to scam people because of it.
author: Bar Mor Hazut

title: '[I] don't owe anyone free Wi-Fi': Entitled neighbor bad-mouths the guy next door after he refuses to share his Wi-Fi password, comeuppance gets served throughout the neighborhood
description: This entitled neighbor 'forgot' to pay his Internet bill, then proceeded to corner the guy next door about using his Wi-Fi from afar, but he stood his ground. What's mine is mine. If you're a reasonable adult paying your bills on time and enjoying the pleasures of a regular paycheck and a comfortable life, you're entitled to bask in the spoils of your work. Internet, power, water, and gas are all a few 'luxuries' that get dealt with on autopay, deemed essentials to enjoying your living space to its full potential. So when your neighbor comes to try and reach into your home and your safe haven, they're risking the integrity of your hard-earned livelihood. With that in mind, when the stranger next door approached the guy in our next story about using his Wi-Fi password, he rightfully refused. Adamant about protecting his home's security and Internet integrity, he shut down the advancing neighbor. But that wasn't enough to stop him from bad-mouthing him all over the neighborhood… Keep scrolling for the full story.
author: Jesse Kessenheimer

title: Bride stops wedding on her big day to rescue four stray kittens near the ceremony, she adopts them all on the happiest day of her life
description: Ah, mawwiage. Mawwiage is what brings us togevver, today (this is a Princess Bride reference for all of you clueless as to why we are horribly misspelling 'marriage'). But really though, marriage is a beautiful thing. It's the happiest day of your life, hopefully. It's also a very stressful day. For those of you who are married, you know the craziness that comes on your wedding day. You have a schedule that's packed tighter than a cat in a purrito, there is no margin for error and no time for any distractions.That is, unless, the cat distribution system knocks on your door. Imagine you're getting ready, your hair and makeup are done, you take your two-minute and 30-second break in the schedule to walk around and get some fresh air….and then you hear some meowing. Not just one meow, but four, eight, sixteen meows! Naturally, you investigate. You find four kittens in the venue, so what else can you do except put your wedding on hold and rescue the smol little babies? That's exactly what happened below, so scroll down to watch the whole heartwarming video!
author: Blake Seidel

title: 24 Orange Cat Memes With 0 Brain Cells and 1,000 Silly on the Hooman Humor Meter
description: Are you a pawrent of an orange cat? If you are, on the one hand - you have less to worry about, because you have the cat but minus the brain. So, technically, it's less to worry about, because it's literally less of a thing in the cat. But on the other hand, the fact your orange buddy has yet to obtain the single brain cell all orange cats share creates other things you should worry about. Like the orange cat behavior. And yes, we're 200% sure that if you're an orange cat pawrent you know exactly what sort of behavior we're talking about. The orange kind.For everyone else who does not pawrent an orange feline friend, let us demonstrate it to you with the power of memes. We gathered some cat memes that demonstrate the power of a 0 brain cell orange cat to create silly chaos all around them. But it's not just the chaos, it's the… orangeness. And it's definitely great for meme material. It's no wonder this genre of cat memes is flourishing.

title: Thanos SNAP
description: For whatever reason, Gabe simply has never been subject to TikTok. Whatever it's doing, however it's trying to do it, it simply doesn't plug into his dealio. I never got into Reddit really, whatever its charms, and that's the bifurcation. They could ban TikTok, or not ban it, or only make it available between the hours of Midnight and One O'Clock, and he literally wouldn't know. I have sent him three to four hundred TikToks over the last six years or so and he just says he doesn't have it and will never have it. I suspect it's like when your cat gives you an inside-out mouse, and you're supposed to appreciate it, but you want nothing to do with it in any way, shape, or form. For a variety of reasons. You won't suddenly be inspired to investigate mouse recipes. You know?

title: CodeSOD: The 5-Digit Session Identifier
description: Sawyer was talking with a co-worker about how their unique session IDs got created. The concern was that they were only five characters long, which meant there could easily be collisions. They started by looking at the random number generation function. Public Function RandomNumberGenerator(ByVal min As Integer, ByVal max As Integer, Optional ByVal numDecimals As Integer = 0) As String '*** the generates a number as a string Dim strNum As New StringBuilder Dim rnd As New System.Random Dim i, x, n As Integer Try i = rnd.Next(min, max) If numDecimals > 0 Then Try strNum.Append("9", numDecimals) n = CType(strNum.ToString, Int32) x = rnd.Next(0, n) Catch ex As Exception x = 1 End Try End If strNum.Remove(0, strNum.Length) strNum.Append(i.ToString()) If numDecimals > 0 Then strNum.Append(".") If numDecimals > 99 Then numDecimals = 99 End If strNum.Append(x.ToString("D" & numDecimals.ToString())) End If Return strNum.ToString Catch Return "1.00" End Try End Function You always know it's going to be bad when you see the random number generator returns a string. If numDecimals is zero, the code is bad, but vaguely sane. Generate a random number using the built in functions, then return it- as a string. It's the use of numDecimals which makes this weird. We start by appending "9"s to our string builder, converting it to an integer, and then generating a random number from zero to whatever number of nines we're using. This is the code of someone who hates and fears logarithms. Then we clear out our string builder because we're starting over with the actual number. Then we append a ".", then we append our number, formatted with our number of decimals string, which we force to be no larger than 99. And this is where we get the special kind of weird. When we're generating our random decimal number, we do this: strNum.Append("9", numDecimals). This is going to put numDecimals 9s on the string. E.g., if numDecimals is 9, this would set strNum to be 999999999. Thus, when we generate a random number, we generate one between 0 and 99999999. But, when we append that formatted value to the string, we do this: If numDecimals > 99 Then numDecimals = 99 End If strNum.Append(x.ToString("D" & numDecimals.ToString())) Here, we're treating numDecimals as a format string. We're only ever going to output two digits. The only good news is that while this random function was used everywhere, it wasn't used to generate their random IDs. The bad news, this is how their random IDs. Public Function RandomQueryStringGenerator() As String '*** the generates an alpha-numeric string 5 digits long such as aa7bb Dim strPwd As New StringBuilder Dim rnd As New System.Random Dim i As Integer Try For x As Integer = 1 To 5 Select Case x Case 1, 2, 4, 5, 8, 9 i = rnd.Next(97, 122) If i Mod 2 = 0 Then strPwd.Append(Chr(i).ToString().ToUpper()) Else strPwd.Append(Chr(i).ToString()) End If Case Else i = rnd.Next(0, 9) strPwd.Append(i.ToString()) End Select Next x Return strPwd.ToString() Catch Return String.Empty End Try End Function [Advertisement] Utilize BuildMaster to release your software with confidence, at the pace your business demands.
